Explore & Summarize Data by Suraag Gupta

This report is for the Financial Contributions to Presidential Campaigns dataset. The state used for this dataset is Ohio.

Looking at the summary of the variables, some of my observations are that: - It seems that cmte_id & cand_id are very similar and could possibly have the same semantic references. - Looking at contbr_nm, it seems that several people made contributions multiple times. - All the contributors are in the state of Ohio. - The discrepancies between contbr_employer and contbr_occupation are somewhat strange, as I would expect values such as RETIRED to match. - The contribution quantities are fairly small, looking at the mean and median values. The large negative number for the minimum is an interesting data point, I wouldnt expect there to be negative contributions, or withdrawals here. Hopefully, the receipt_desc or memo_text will explain what is going on there.

This plot shows quite clearly that the primary recipient of contributions in the state of Ohio was Hilary Clinton, with Bernie Sanders and Trump coming in second & third, respectively, at nearly half the number. Have to keep in mind that this isnt for the total amount of contributions, just how many times the candidate was contributed to.

Looking at some of the observations of contbr_city, it quickly becomes clear that the data hasnt be cleaned, with several misspellings present for the same city. Restricting the plot to cities with higher counts shows what most Ohio residents would expect. Columbus at the top, with Cincinnati close behind.

Somewhat unexpected to see people contributing so many times. The main question that arises here is who out of these people will appear on the highest amount plot.

I wasnt expecting to see the Retired contributors make up such a significant portion of the dataset, this should be interesting to investigate soon.

Here I used a log10 for the contribution amounts here to visualize better. The majority of donations seem to be between the $10 to $100 range.

As would be expected here, most of the contributions were made in in the year of the election, with the majority coming in what appears to be near the middle or end of the summer.

Most of the contributions are directed towards the general & presidential elections.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The Financial Contributions dataset for Ohio has 167,259 observations of 18 variables. Committee ID, Candidate ID, & Candidate Name seem to refer to the same pieces of data. Most of the variables are unordered factors, due to being names, locations, or reference IDs.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I think the main features of the dataset are the candidates & the contribution amounts.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Supporting the above two features would be the contribution dates/the election type & the occupation of the contributors. ### Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset? I created new dataframes for the first three plots, so that I could have an easier time subsetting the data based on counts.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

There were misspellings in the contributor city, zip code, employer, & occupation features, but I did not attempt to fix these. I changed the receipt dates from Strings to Dates to make calculations and plots involving them easier.

Bivariate Plots Section

In line with the contribution counts, Hillary Clinton maintains the highest total contribution value, but unexpectedly, John Kasich has a surprisingly high contribution value ranking at 2nd, while only having the 6th highest contribution count. This could indicate the types of voters/contributors that supported him. Similarly, Bernie & Trump switched roles with counts & amounts.

Here we see that contributions towards the primary elections lasted for a long while, and consisted of most of the contributions, which is in line with the earlier plot of election type counts.

Slightly unexpectedly, while Columbus may have had the highest number of contributors, Cincinnati had a higher contribution value.

Comparing this plot to that of the one with the highest contribution counts, there are no matching names. Its possible that contributors will either make multiple small contributions over a period of time or they will make a few large contributions.

Moving on to the occupations of the contributors, retirees still take the prime position with donation amounts, that too by a huge margin.

Using the 95% quantile for the contribution amounts and cutting out the negatives, which after doing some exploration seemed to be mostly refunds, it seems that most of the contributions came as the election itself approached.

Two interesting things can be seen in this plot. First, most of the contributions are larger in value, as only a small chunk of the plot has values less than about $50. Second, contributions to Trump continued even after he won.

The above plots for the top 3 contributed candidates have similar trends. Few contributions made in the year prior to the election, but generally of higher value, while the year of the election is where most of the data lies.

This plot is fairly different from the previous 3. While the information is all gathered in a shorter time frame, it seems that, compared to the other candidates, there are few contributors that donated less than $50, with the majority of the values seeming to be at $100 or $250.

A similar situation with the individual candidates is visible with the retired contributors. This trend is likely identical with all candidates and contributor occupations.

The contribution amounts based on the election are in line with the contribution counts, with the majority of it going towards the primary election.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Overall, the contribution amounts and contribution counts produced similar relationships through the dataset, with only a few notable exceptions that were pointed out above.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

One of the main factors I observed was the date variable. Depending on when the candidates were no longer considered in the running, contributions either completely stopped or slowed down significantly. The amount of contributions increased closer to the election, while the amount of the contribution didnt seem to be directly affected by the date.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

It seems that the strongest relationship is between date and amount.

Multivariate Plots Section

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

The first multivariate plot created reinforced the smaller contribution values at higher quantities. The second plot illustrated how the funds were split for particular elections.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

The second plot, with the candidates vs the contribution dates colorized by the election type was expected, but still somewhat interesting to see. As the candidates lost in the primary elections, their funds disappeared, and for the winners, all the funding went directly to the coming general election. Its likely that this is just a sorting and organizational detail made by the committee, as the contributors would not need to make the specification as to which election the funds went toward.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

I thought this plot was interesting because I didnt expect retirees to make up such a huge portion of the contributors.

Plot Two

Description Two

This plot is interesting because it demonstrates that even with a much larger amount of financial support, the top 2 candidates here lost the election. It would be interesting to see if there were similar situations in previous election years, as Donald Trump has a significant amount of wealth on his own, which may have also been a factor in his relatively lower amount of contribution.

Plot Three

Description Three

Perhaps the most obvious of the three plots, showing that the bulk of the contributions came in closer to the date of the general election.

Reflection

I was slightly disappointed with what information there was to find in this dataset. While the insights and plots created certainly had a good amount of information to share, there werent as many variables to explore as I would have liked. In addition, with the sheer quantity of different contributors, cities, occupations, & employers, it was a little hard to explore everything as much as I would have liked. There may be more insights to discover using smaller subsets based on the contributors, cities, and occupations, after cleaning the data and having a better method to split up the information and plots that rely on factored variables.
